Making a mess of Prawn by starting work on these TextBox things.Actually my aim is to make it easy to render simple tables, but for now there's TextBox, which intrudes but then does not intrude enough. The idea is sort of similar to the bounding boxes, except this is only for text and changing a TextBox's width changes its height, kind of like in HTML.nnIn addition to introducing the Prawn::TextBox class (which adds nothing to the namespace you'd use when doing pdf.whatever, but requires you to use an ugly render_on_pdf call) I moved greedy_wrap into AFM, but then couldn't get it to work right, so I rewrote it as naive_wrap. I think it does more or less the same thing.n

How ruby strings are converted to PDF Strings depends on if they're going into a content stream or not - Inside a content stream, our font magic has alredy converted the   string into Identity-H encoding, so I just needs to be hexified - Outside a content stream, the string is just regular UTF-8, and it   needs to be converted to UTF-16 with a BOM, then hexified   - This means we can have international text for things like metadata, bookmarks, annotations, etc

templates: all stringss outside content streams should be hex strings* strings that are valid UTF-8 will be converted to UTF-16 with a BOMn  before they're written to the new filen* strings that are not UTF-8 will be are treated as byte strings aren  left untouchedn* Fixes an issue reported by Joel Nylund. A byte string for an indexedn  colour space was being written out as a LiteralString, which haven  complex escaping rules that weren't being met correctly. This bypassesn  the escaping, hex strings are *MUCH* simplern

Improve escaping of LiteralStrings to suit spec* the spec defines 8 bytes that need to be escaped by a backslash, wen  were only escaping 4 of themn* The regexp we were using didn't work on non utf-8 strings as it wasn  character encoding sensitive. Some LiteralStrings are for binary datan  (like encrypted strings, or index colourspaces) so we needed the 'n'n  option on the regexp to ensure it wil escape the 8 bytes in *ALL*n  strings, regardless of encodingn* second part of the fix to the issue reported by Joel Nylundn

Defer cell min_width calculation until neededmin_width was set in the Prawn::Table::Cell initializer and so wasnignoring any changes that happened after the cells were built (such asnin the block passed to Prawn::Table.new). So tables with a small widthnwould still raise CannotFit errors, even if you tried to shrink the sizenor padding in the initializer to make it work.nnThis fix defers min / max width calculations until they are requested,nwhich only happens when cells are actually being positioned.nnThanks to Liviu for reporting this issue with a simple test case.n

Don't restore y-position on stretchy bboxesWhen starting a bounding box at the bottom of a page (for example, usingnspan starting at the end of a page), drawing some text (advancing to thennext page), and then closing out the bbox / span, Prawn would restorenthe original (bottom) y-position, thus stretching the bbox to the heightnof the page. This commit resolves that issue.nnCloses #255.n

Refactor so images via Pathname are read in binmode* Separate out image IO opening and verification logicn* test that embedded images parse correctly (this was the problem thatn  was being masked before)n* Add simple matcher to tidy up checking XObject parseabilityn* fixes prawnpdf/prawn#570:nnPathname instances respond to #read but not #binmode, and the old codenwas assuming that anything which responded to #read was an IO, with thenresult that Pathname instances were beign treated as IO's and gettingnread called on them, bypassing File.binread (things respondingnto #binmode have that called so with a real IO it would have #readncalled after it had been put into binmode...nnThe fix is simple enough: treat everything that responds to binmode asnan IO (IO's and Files), and anything else treat as a path, and open itn'rb'.n

Allow for pluggable image handlersThis commit does two things, it move recognition for if an image classncan support a given image into that class, and will attempt to find annimage handler for any given image among any class defined inside thenPrawn::Images module.nnThis makes it easier to add support for additional image formatsnwithout directly modifying the prawn core library.n

Require image handlers to register themselvesI added Prawn::Images.add_image_handler so code can tell prawnnexplicitly what classes to try to use when searching for an imagenhandler for a given image.nnWe automaticlly load our PNG and JPG handlers for backwardsncompatability.n

Alternative PNG alpha-channel extractionAccording to PNG spec filtering happens on a per-byte basis and usesncorresponding bytes from other pixels. This means that we don't have to actuallynunfilter all the data. Instead it's possible to split pixel data into planes.nnA few points to note:nn* Filters are reused from original imagen* Resulting opaque PNG uses the same filtered datan* Resulting mask PNG image uses the same filteres datan* Both resulting images are valid PNG imagesn* All the unfiltering masth is skipped which results in great boostsn

Avoid setting y position unless modified in canvasThis is a clarification on the desired behavior of bounding boxes, whichnessentially states that if the user does not modify the ynposition in a bounding box that is either stretchy ornhas its position held, the original y position will be restored.nnThe only realistic condition I can think of for this isnwhen doing vector drawings which do not actually modify the cursornposition, or possibly when doing conditional logic within a boundingnbox call. However, this does fix the problem discovered in #523,nwhere calling canvas without modifying the y position endsnup putting the cursor at the absolute top of the page, outsidenof the margins.nnThis is not an ideal fix, but it (mostly) preserves existingnbehavior while providing sane behavior for an edge case.n

Transitional extraction of templatesThis commit is a squashed subset of #640, which begins thenprocess of extracting templates out of Prawn::Document andninto an extension. It's not complete, but it's functionalnenough where I'd like to include it in release fornuser testing. It accomplishes two main goals:nn* Disables templates by default in Prawnnn* Allows those who will use the future prawn-templates gemnto try it out as an extension by requiring prawn/templatesnnThe way I extracted the code is not meant to be a permanentnsolution. We will need to move away from a module-based monkeynpatch to some sort of object-oriented solution, and we shouldnaim to cut down the duplication of code in the templatesnextension. But this is something we can do later.nnWe also need to finish extracting the lower-level featuresnthat templates depend upon, but that too can be done inna future release. This patch is primarily about removingnthe top-level use of the feature so that we can be surenwe didn't break anything critical in the process of doing so.n

Vastly improve Prawn's AFM font encoding handlingA squashed merge of #793, containing the following improvements:nn* Text for all Prawn methods is now UTF-8-in, UTF-8-out, so the userndoes not need to handle Windows-1252 strings.nn* Internally, we're now using Ruby's M17n system to handle the encodingninto Windows-1252, so text.encoding will come back as Windows-1252nwhen `AFM#normalize_encoding` is called, rather than `ASCII-8Bit`nn* When using AFM fonts + ASCII only text, no warning will be seen.nn* When using AFM fonts + non-ASCII characters that are supported inn Windows-1252, users will see a warning about the limitedninternationalization support, along with a recommendation to use a TTFn font instead.nn* The warning includes instructions on how to disable it (just setn`Prawn::Font::AFM.hide_m17_warning = true`)nn* When using AFM fonts + non-ASCII characters that are NOT supported inn* WIndows-1252, an exception will be raised rather than replacing w.n `_`.nn* None of the above will apply to anyone using TTF fonts with sane UTF-8nsupport, everything should just work for those folks.n

Fix styled width_of when using TTFs.Previously, width_of calculations on styled text were relying on thendocument font's `name` attribute in order to look up the appropriatenfont style. This doesn't work for TTF fonts, since the name is a fullnpath to a single style of font, and the Prawn must know about the fontnfamily in order to find another style.nnThis update uses the family instead, which allows the width_ofncalculations to work properly with TTFs, and doesn't appear to cause anynregressions based on existing specs.nn(Squashed commit of #827)n

Gradients can have multiple stops to blend more than two colorsPreviously, only two colors could be specified in a gradient: the startnand end colors.  This change allows any number of colors to be specified,nalong with the position between 0 and 1 as to where they should be displayed.nnThis change also comes with a change to the format of the `fill_gradient`nand `stroke_gradient` methods.  You can continue to use the old methodnparameters and only specify two colors, or use the new keyword argumentsnto specify arbitrary stops.nnAs a bonus, if you use the new method style, `apply_transformations` isnset true automatically (see below).n
Use a Hash for position-specified gradient stopsIt looks nicer than using an Array of Arrays. #902n

Remove superfluous pdf-core requiresWe require `pdf/core` in `lib/prawn.rb`, and were requiringn`pdf/core/text` and `pdf/core/byte_string` in `lib/prawn/text.rb` andn`lib/prawn/security.rb` respectively.nnThose second requires were causing double-loads and warnings underncertain circumstances because of a bug in Rubyn(https://bugs.ruby-lang.org/issues/10222).nnWe use objects under the `PDF::Core` namespace freely throught Prawn andnthose two requires seem to be both out of character (in the rest of thencodebase it's assumed that `PDF::Core` has already been required), andnoverkill (`pdf-core`'s codebase itself generally assumes that all thenobjects under its namespace are already required).nnI think it's safe to just remove these requires deeper into `pdf-core` -nit makes these double-load problems go away and is more in keeping withnthe way the code is structured.nnThere is the larger question of the architecture of `pdf-core` u00e2u0080u0093 whethernit's a grab-bag of objects and modules to be picked-and-chosen from, orna single entity that should be used complete. I don't think there's ansignificant impact to that process from this approach to removing thenwarnings.n
